1.1 Project Description

The Agentic AI Platform is designed to enhance how employees execute operational and business workflows by introducing autonomous AI agents capable of performing multi-step tasks across web and enterprise applications within the user’s working environment.

Delivered through a browser-based interface and a centralized orchestration platform, these agents can understand user intent, navigate applications, retrieve and analyze data, and execute actions using the user’s existing system access. In addition to task execution, agents support capabilities such as Q&A, summarization, contextual reasoning, and report generation, enabling users to derive insights and complete workflows more efficiently.

The platform also enables agents to be refined and reused over time, improving accuracy and consistency across repeated tasks.

Teams today rely on manual navigation across multiple systems for tasks such as data retrieval, reporting, approvals, and operational updates.

Existing automation solutions are rigid, difficult to maintain, and lack contextual understanding.

There is no unified capability to assist users in executing workflows intelligently while ensuring governance, reuse, and scalability.



UC 1 – Multi-Step Workflow Execution by Agents

Enable agents to autonomously execute end-to-end workflows across web and enterprise applications within the user’s browser session, including navigation, data extraction, reasoning, and action execution.

👉 (Core capability — keep this as foundation)

UC 2 – Personal Agent Creation & Reuse

Allow users to create, save, and reuse task-specific agents for repetitive workflows, enabling consistent execution and reducing manual effort over time.

👉 (User-level reuse — clearly separate from marketplace)

UC 3 – Internal Agent Marketplace (Governed Sharing)

Provide a centralized platform for teams to publish, discover, and reuse agents with governance controls such as access permissions, metadata tagging, and usage tracking.

👉 (Team-level sharing — not personal reuse)

UC 4 – Human-in-the-Loop Review & Approval

Enable policy-driven approval workflows where agents can pause execution for user validation before performing sensitive or high-impact actions, ensuring compliance and traceability.

👉 (Governance / control — unique)

UC 5 – On-Demand Task-Level Agents (Short-Term)

Support ephemeral agents for quick, one-time tasks such as summarization, data extraction, or analysis, without maintaining long-term state.

👉 (Short-term / Comet-style usage)

UC 6 – Persistent Operational Agents (Long-Term)

Enable long-running agents that support recurring workflows such as monitoring, reporting, or periodic task execution with maintained context over time.

👉 (Long-term — clearly distinct from UC5)

UC 7 – Secure & Controlled Execution Environment

Ensure all agent actions operate within a secure framework with enterprise controls such as domain whitelisting, sensitive data masking, and audit logging to enforce compliance and prevent data leakage.

👉 (Security — separate concern)
UC 8 – External System Integration:
Enable agents to interact with external systems such as APIs, documents, and emails in addition to browser-based workflows. All interactions are performed using the user’s access and governed by enterprise security controls, allowing agents to execute end-to-end workflows across multiple data sources.
